(43, 'What is Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'Atos Cloud Foundry is an integrated cloud platform that accelerates your time-to-market for next generation digital applications or the platform to pitch for developers that they could code in the programming language and Web framework of their choice without worrying about the underlying IT environment.\r\n\r\nIt enables you to:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Create cloud native applications using a range of programming languages framework and application services.</li>\r\n 	<li>Deploy applications to your choice of supported IaaS target such as private or public clouds around the globe based geographical location to meet your data sovereignty or network latency needs and avoid vendor lock-in.</li>\r\n 	<li>Deliver updates to your cloud applications continuously without downtime</li>\r\n 	<li>Have multiple versions of your live application at the same time</li>\r\n 	<li>Dynamically scale your applications without changing any code</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 1, 1, 0, 0, 133, 'admin', '12-07-2017'),
(49, 'Who are the intended customers?', 1, 'Any organization/enterprise looking for Cloud – PaaS &amp; interested in a fully managed enterprise PaaS to overcome issues such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Speed of development of enterprise application, instead spending time on hardware and software issues(improved development productivity)</li>\r\n 	<li>An organization who want to eliminate the overhead of cost of maintaining hardware &amp; software</li>\r\n 	<li>An enterprise who is having issue to scale up their existing application running</li>\r\n 	<li>Enterprise facing issue in switching in different environment’s (Development &amp; Test-System, Integration &amp; UAT etc.)</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 2, 1, 0, 0, 120, 'admin', '12-07-2017'),
(52, 'How can I get started with Atos Cloud Foundry and onboarding of users?', 1, 'For your own dedicated instance of Cloud Foundry, contact Christophe Bon (<a href="mailto:christophe.bon@atos.net">christophe.bon@atos.net</a>).\r\n\r\nFor on-boarding of new-users on Atos cloud Foundry platform.Users need to send their request with the attachment of on-boarding form in <a href="gcsi-coe-ops-pltmgt@atos.net">gcsi-coe-ops-pltmgt@atos.net</a> mailbox.\r\n\r\n<em>Please find the link of on-boarding form :- <a href="https://acf-console.s3.amazonaws.com/ACF+2017.07-CF-CLI+User+Guide_new.docx">https://acf-console.s3.amazonaws.com/ACF+2017.07-CF-CLI+User+Guide_new.docx</a></em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo register for a trial account on the Atos Cloud Foundry Trial, send your request to Atos Global Devops <a href="gcsi-coe-ops-pltmgt@atos.net">( gcsi-coe-ops-pltmgt@atos.net) </a>with your details like E-mail ID, Organization and Country. An account will be made for you within 1-2 working days.', '', 3, 1, 0, 0, 124, 'admin', '12-07-2017'),
(61, 'How many programming languages for application development are supported in Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'Cloud Foundry supports several popular programming languages and their frameworks as follows:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Ruby</li>\r\n 	<li>PHP (incl. Wordpress)</li>\r\n 	<li>Node.js</li>\r\n 	<li>Java</li>\r\n 	<li>Clojure</li>\r\n 	<li>Go Lang</li>\r\n 	<li>Python</li>\r\n 	<li>Scala</li>\r\n 	<li>Apple Swift</li>\r\n 	<li>Microsoft .Net</li>\r\n 	<li>TOMEE</li>\r\n 	<li>Jboss</li>\r\n 	<li>Wildfly</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 4, 1, 0, 0, 114, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(64, 'Application Services available or supported within Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, '<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US"><b>Application</b> <b>Services Supported in HA mode</b>”</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF Kafka</span></li>\r\n 	<li>CF ELK</li>\r\n 	<li>Broker Aurora</li>\r\n 	<li>CF Elasticsearch</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Application</b> <b>Services available for end users to explore (NON-HA by default)</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF MySQL/MariaDB + UI</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF RabbitMQ</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF Redis</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF MongoDB + UI</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF PostgreSQL + UI</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF Memcached</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF ElasticSearch (beta version)</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF Neo4J</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF RiakCS</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF Cassandra</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">CF CouchDB + UI</span></p>\r\n<p class="x_MsoListParagraph"><span lang="EN-US">Abacus</span></p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 5, 1, 0, 0, 113, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(67, 'What are 12 factor applications?', 1, 'The twelve-factor app is a methodology for building software-as-a-service apps that meets following requirements:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Use declarative formats for setup automation, to minimize time and cost for new developers joining the project;</li>\r\n 	<li>Have a clean contract with the underlying operating system, offering maximum portability between execution environments;</li>\r\n 	<li>Are suitable for deployment on modern cloud platforms, obviating the need for servers and systems administration;</li>\r\n 	<li>Minimize divergence between development and production, enabling continuous deployment for maximum agility;</li>\r\n 	<li>And can scale up without significant changes to tooling, architecture, or development practices.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe twelve-factor methodology can be applied to apps written in any programming language, and which use any combination of backing services (database, queue, memory cache, etc).For further reference visit: 12factor.net', '', 6, 1, 0, 0, 113, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(70, 'What is micro service architecture?', 1, 'Micro services is a software architecture style in which complex applications are composed of small, independent processes communicating with each other using language-agnostic APIs.  These services are small, highly decoupled and focus on doing a small task, facilitating a modular approach to system-building.', '', 7, 1, 0, 0, 111, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(73, 'How Docker, Kubernetes &amp; Cloud Foundry is different from Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, '<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>“Docker &amp; Cloud Foundry”</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n“Deploying an App with Docker” <a href="https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fdocs.cloudfoundry.org%2Fdevguide%2Fdeploy-apps%2Fpush-docker.html&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cprashanth.janardanan%40atos.net%7C95d370b20f6a43e2478308d6dd1bfa0b%7C33440fc6b7c7412cbb730e70b0198d5a%7C0%7C0%7C636939509555206710&amp;sdata=uS4t1jNDTksr0mfE70bdxVdtRnYbAH8VIunLZglgVfc%3D&amp;reserved=0">https://docs.cloudfoundry.org/devguide/deploy-apps/push-docker.html</a>\r\n\r\n“Using Docker in Cloud Foundry” <a href="https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fdocs.cloudfoundry.org%2Fadminguide%2Fdocker.html&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cprashanth.janardanan%40atos.net%7C95d370b20f6a43e2478308d6dd1bfa0b%7C33440fc6b7c7412cbb730e70b0198d5a%7C0%7C0%7C636939509555216698&amp;sdata=gDEs%2BXZYi9yBDc6Rfd%2BkjMiEKGqiveuDNIQFkcgahd8%3D&amp;reserved=0">https://docs.cloudfoundry.org/adminguide/docker.html</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>“<strong>Kubernetes &amp; Cloud Foundry</strong>”</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<a href="https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cloudfoundry.org%2Fcontainer-runtime%2F&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cprashanth.janardanan%40atos.net%7C95d370b20f6a43e2478308d6dd1bfa0b%7C33440fc6b7c7412cbb730e70b0198d5a%7C0%7C0%7C636939509555216698&amp;sdata=2HmGc8Z8A3TiaKbFVnF45tX%2BoYk7wNgXIJtFOn3Wlo4%3D&amp;reserved=0">            https://www.cloudfoundry.org/container-runtime/</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAtos Cloud foundry is a platform as a service (PaaS) which makes it really easy for developers to run their applications in the cloud without having to worry about any infrastructure. To push applications to the cloud, developers only push their (web) applications; everything else – from the hardware up to the application servers – is provided by the platform. In addition to hosting applications, Atos Cloud Foundry also provide services like databases, caches and messaging systems that developers can leverage, again without having to set up any infrastructure. Furthermore,Atos Cloud Foundry provides scalability of applications and auto-recovery; it provides logging dashboards and more administration functionality many developers don’t want to worry about.\r\n\r\nDocker is a container technology to package full application stacks so that these containers can easily be run in different environments. This portability is achieved by packaging not only the core applications (your own code), but also the complete underlying stack you need to run applications including application servers, Java run-time environment, configuration and other dependencies. Docker uses Linux as operating system and leverages concepts like Linux namespaces to run multiple applications in sandboxes. Containers are more portable since all you need are Linux Docker environments while for Atos Cloud Foundry packaged applications you have more prerequisites, the Atos Cloud Foundry run-times and services.', '', 8, 1, 0, 0, 113, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(76, 'What is containerization?', 1, 'Containerization is a lightweight alternative to full machine virtualization that involves encapsulating an application in a container with its own operating environment. This provides many of the benefits of loading an application onto a virtual machine, as the application can be run on any suitable physical machine without any worries about dependencies.\r\n\r\nDocker is a technology for creating and running Linux "containers." For example, A Docker container for java app will consist of a Docker image, which will basically contain a filesystem with all the things needed to run your app (JVM, your source code, etc.), and docker container metadata, which tells the Docker daemon how to run the app inside the image (e.g. what environment variables to set, what ports to expose, what commands to run, etc.).', '', 9, 1, 0, 0, 109, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(79, 'How can I run my own Docker image on Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'All atos cloud foundry instance are by-default Docker enabled.\r\n\r\nUsers simply need to push app using following command /syntax:\r\n<blockquote>cf push   App-name  --docker -image  user/docker-image-name\r\n\r\nOption:\r\n\r\nApp-name:  name of your app\r\n\r\nuser/docker-image-name :  user account name/ name of docker image created for app.</blockquote>\r\nFurther information can be found from the following link:” <a href="https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fdocs.cloudfoundry.org%2Fdevguide%2Fdeploy-apps%2Fpush-docker.html&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cprashanth.janardanan%40atos.net%7C95d370b20f6a43e2478308d6dd1bfa0b%7C33440fc6b7c7412cbb730e70b0198d5a%7C0%7C0%7C636939509555216698&amp;sdata=ZTTNRv1kQNSUbdRKaWDUrycsvPF0c2mowynYy9v1V2o%3D&amp;reserved=0">https://docs.cloudfoundry.org/devguide/deploy-apps/push-docker.html</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Note –</strong> The Cloud Controller always runs Docker containers on Diego with user namespaces enabled. This security restriction prevents certain features, such as the ability to mount FuseFS devices, from working in Docker containers.\r\n\r\nTo mitigate security concerns, Atos Cloud Foundry recommends that you run only trusted Docker containers on the platform.', '', 10, 1, 0, 0, 110, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(82, 'What target IAAS are supported in Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'Atos Cloud Foundry supports the following IaaS:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Amazon Web Services (AWS)</li>\r\n 	<li>VMware vSphere – Enterprise Private Cloud(EPC)</li>\r\n 	<li>Azure</li>\r\n 	<li>Google(GCP)</li>\r\n 	<li>Alibaba</li>\r\n 	<li>Huawei</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 11, 1, 0, 0, 109, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(85, 'What are the port limitations of Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'Applications running on Atos Cloud Foundry receive requests through the URLs configured for the application\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Atos Cloud Foundry applications receive HTTPS requests on ports 80 and 443 only.</li>\r\n 	<li>The TCP/WebSocket communication happens through port 4443.</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 12, 1, 0, 0, 109, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(88, 'What is Diego?', 1, 'Diego is the core architecture of Atos Cloud Foundry to help scheduling, deploying and manage the application containers.\r\n\r\nFurther information can be found from the following link:-<a href="https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fdocs.cloudfoundry.org%2Fconcepts%2Fdiego%2Fdiego-architecture.html&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cprashanth.janardanan%40atos.net%7C95d370b20f6a43e2478308d6dd1bfa0b%7C33440fc6b7c7412cbb730e70b0198d5a%7C0%7C0%7C636939509555226697&amp;sdata=K2vn%2FSf69EJAsEsxrf0emIC0DI9LjG%2FItCaTwCkmryw%3D&amp;reserved=0">https://docs.cloudfoundry.org/concepts/diego/diegoarchitecture.html</a>', '', 13, 1, 0, 0, 115, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(103, 'What is Vertical vs Horizontal scale?', 1, 'Horizontal scalability is the ability to increase capacity by adding multiple hardware or software entities so that they work as a single logical unit.\r\n\r\nWhen servers are clustered, the original server is being scaled out horizontally.\r\n\r\nIf a cluster requires more resources to improve performance and provide high availability (HA), an administrator can scale out by adding more servers to the cluster.\r\n\r\nAn important advantage of horizontal scalability is that it can provide administrators with the ability to increase capacity on the fly.\r\n\r\nAnother advantage is that in theory, horizontal scalability is only limited by how many entities can be connected successfully.\r\n\r\nThe distributed storage system Cassandra, for example, runs on top of hundreds of commodity nodes spread across different data centers.\r\n\r\nBecause the commodity hardware is scaled out horizontally, Cassandra is fault tolerant and does not have a single point of failure (SPoF).\r\n\r\nVertical scalability, on the other hand, increases capacity by adding more resources, such as more memory or an additional CPU, to a machine.\r\n\r\nScaling vertically, which is also called scaling up, usually requires downtime while new resources are being added and has limits that are defined by hardware.\r\n\r\nWhen Amazon RDS customers need to scale vertically, for example, they can switch from a smaller to a bigger machine, but Amazon''s largest RDS instance has only 68 GB of memory.', '', 14, 1, 0, 0, 102, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(106, 'How can I see my application logs?', 1, '<blockquote>Using CF-CLI command as below\r\n\r\ncf logs YOUR-APP-NAME\r\n\r\nWhere [APP-NAME] is name of your application pushed with name</blockquote>', '', 15, 1, 0, 0, 109, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(112, 'Does Atos Cloud Foundry support persistence store?', 1, 'Applications running on Atos Cloud Foundry should not write files to the local file system for the following reasons:\r\n\r\nLocal file system storage is short-lived. When an application instance crashes or stops, the resources assigned to that instance are reclaimed by the platform including any local disk changes made since the app started. When the instance is restarted, the application will start with a new disk image. Although your application can write local files while it is running, the files will disappear after the application restarts.\r\n\r\nInstances of the same application do not share a local file system. Each application instance runs in its own isolated container. Thus a file written by one instance is not visible to other instances of the same application. If the files are temporary, this should not be a problem. However, if your application needs the data in the files to persist across application restarts, or the data needs to be shared across all running instances of the application, the local file system should not be used. We recommend using a shared data service like a database or blobstore for this purpose.\r\n\r\nFor example, instead of using the local file system, you can use a Cloud Foundry service such as the MongoDB document database or a relational database like MySQL or Postgres. Another option is to use cloud storage providers such as Amazon S3, Google Cloud Storage, Dropbox, or Box. If your application needs to communicate across different instances of it, consider a cache like Redis or a messaging-based architecture with RabbitMQ.', '', 16, 1, 0, 0, 110, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(115, 'Does Atos Cloud Foundry support .Net applications?', 1, 'Atos Cloud Foundry being a Cloud Foundry Foundation certified distribution, it also provides .NET applications support.\r\n\r\nFurther information can be found from the following link:-\r\n\r\n<a href="https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fdocs.cloudfoundry.org%2Fbuildpacks%2Fdotnet-core%2Findex.html&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cprashanth.janardanan%40atos.net%7C95d370b20f6a43e2478308d6dd1bfa0b%7C33440fc6b7c7412cbb730e70b0198d5a%7C0%7C0%7C636939509555226697&amp;sdata=SrdYEHxsWwT1cfCWZ1OTHIXDWd1flTWrDG2pnLMgBOE%3D&amp;reserved=0">https://docs.cloudfoundry.org/buildpacks/dotnet-core/index.html</a>', '', 17, 1, 0, 0, 106, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(121, 'What is Bosh-lite?', 1, 'BOSH Lite is a pre-built Vagrant box which includes the Director. It uses containers to emulate VMs which makes it an excellent choice for:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>General BOSH exploration without investing time and resources to configure an IaaS</li>\r\n 	<li>Development of releases (including BOSH itself)</li>\r\n 	<li>Testing releases locally or in CI.</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 18, 1, 0, 0, 110, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(130, 'How can I SSH to VM on which my app is running?', 1, 'This can be done by Configuring SSH Access at the Application Level\r\n\r\n<blockquote>cf enable-ssh enables SSH access to all instances of an app:\r\n\r\n$ cf enable-ssh MY-AWESOME-APP\r\n\r\ncf disable-ssh disables SSH access to all instances of an app:\r\n\r\n$ cf disable-ssh MY-AWESOME-APP</blockquote>', '', 19, 1, 0, 0, 104, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(133, 'What is default response time for application?', 1, 'The application response time varies based on language framework and the buildpack. The default time limits for the phases are as follows:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Upload: 5 minutes maximum</li>\r\n 	<li>Stage: 5 minutes maximum</li>\r\n 	<li>Start: 2 seconds maximum</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 20, 1, 0, 0, 106, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(139, 'How can I leverage for other services on Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'User-provided service instances enable developers to use services that not available in the marketplace with their applications running on Cloud Foundry.\r\n\r\nUser-provided service instances can be used to deliver service credentials to an application, and/or to trigger streaming of application logs to a syslog compatible consumer. These two functions can be used alone or at the same time.\r\n\r\nOnce created, user-provided service instances behave like service instances created through the marketplace.\r\n\r\nCreate a User-Provided Service Instance\r\n\r\nThe alias for cf create-user-provided-service is cf cups\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Deliver Service Credentials to an Application</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSuppose a developer obtains a URL, port, username, and password for communicating with an Oracle database managed outside of Atos Cloud Foundry. The developer could manually create custom environment variables to configure their application with these credentials (of course you would never hard code these credentials in your application!).\r\n\r\nUser-provided service instances enable developers to configure their applications with these using the familiar Application Binding operation and the same application runtime environment variable used by Atos Cloud Foundry to automatically deliver credentials for marketplace services (VCAP_SERVICES).\r\n<blockquote>cf cups SERVICE_INSTANCE -p ''{"username":"admin","password":"pa55woRD"}''</blockquote>\r\nTo create a service instance in interactive mode, use the -p option with a comma-separated list of parameter names. The cf CLI will prompt you for each parameter value.\r\n<blockquote>cf cups SERVICE_INSTANCE -p "host, port, dbname, username, password"</blockquote>\r\nStream Application Logs to a Service\r\n\r\nUser-provided service instances enable developers to stream applications logs to a syslog compatible aggregation or analytics service that isn’t available in the marketplace.\r\n\r\nCreate the user-provided service instance, specifying the URL of the service with the -l option.\r\n<blockquote>cf cups SERVICE_INSTANCE -l syslog://example.log-aggregator.com</blockquote>', '', 21, 1, 0, 0, 106, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(142, 'What is the price model for  Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'Thanks to contact your referent Atos contractual SPOC for further details.\r\n\r\nPlease send your request to Atos Global Devops <a href="https://eur01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Ffaq.apps.eu01.cf.canopy-cloud.com%2Ffaq%2Fgcsi-coe-ops-pltmgt%40atos.net&amp;data=02%7C01%7Cprashanth.janardanan%40atos.net%7C95d370b20f6a43e2478308d6dd1bfa0b%7C33440fc6b7c7412cbb730e70b0198d5a%7C0%7C0%7C636939509555206710&amp;sdata=C8IIwnY74bjcBS6xSyUQ35ViIL5fTBLxJxAXfYZBgCg%3D&amp;reserved=0">( gcsi-coe-ops-pltmgt@atos.net) </a>with your details like E-mail ID,Organization and Country. An account will be made for you within 1-2 working days.', '', 22, 1, 0, 0, 108, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(145, 'What is support model for Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'L1 support provided by Atos Global DevOps (24x7) and L2 support provided by Atos Cloud Foundry Team between 8:00 to 17:00 hours GMT.', '', 23, 1, 0, 0, 110, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(148, 'What is SLA?', 1, 'A service-level agreement (SLA) is a part of a standardized service contract where a service is formally defined. Particular aspects of the service – scope, quality, responsibilities – are agreed between the service provider and the service user. A common feature of an SLA is a contracted delivery time (of the service or performance). As an example, Internet service providers and telcos will commonly include service level agreements within the terms of their contracts with customers to define the level(s) of service being sold in plain language terms. In this case the SLA will typically have a technical definition in terms of mean time between failures (MTBF), mean time to repair or mean time to recovery (MTTR); identifying which party is responsible for reporting faults or paying fees; responsibility for various data rates; throughput; jitter; or similar measurable details.', '', 24, 1, 0, 0, 109, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(151, 'How can I use my own domain for app running in Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'Routing custom top-level domains (e.g. my-custom-domain.com) and custom subdomains (e.g. blog.my-custom-domain.com) to an app running on a Atos Cloud Foundry instance can be achieved using CloudFlare as a DNS provider.\r\n<blockquote>CF CLI command: cf create-domain “you-domain-name”</blockquote>', '', 25, 1, 0, 0, 109, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(154, 'How can I assign extra size RAM/Disk to my app?', 1, 'On the app landing page, there are dropdown available to increase Memory and Disk size.\r\n\r\nUsing CLI-\r\n<blockquote>cf scale myApp -i 5\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\ncf scale myApp -k 512M\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\ncf scale myApp -m 1G</blockquote>', '', 26, 1, 0, 0, 104, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(157, 'How Atos Cloud Foundry support backup?', 1, 'There are no end user backup services supported with Atos Cloud Foundry as of now but we do support customer specific customization in single tenant environment.\r\n\r\nFor example if customer requests backup of user base (UUDB / CC DB) or any specific service like MySQL database for instance.\r\n\r\nUser specific destinations (e.g. S3 backup on EU region etc.) are supported.', '', 27, 1, 0, 0, 104, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(160, 'How can I setup channel between two apps running in Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'Use a messaging service (like RabbitMQ) to communicate between instances of applications. You can also store shared information in a database service or any remote location outside the file system.', '', 28, 1, 0, 0, 103, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(163, 'How can I use external build pack in Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, '<blockquote>cf push –b external_buildpack_url or in your app manifest.yml section you can provide buildpack url</blockquote>', '', 29, 1, 0, 0, 104, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(166, 'How can I move/clone apps within space/orgs?', 1, 'You cannot move an application in the UI. The best way to accomplish this is using the command line by essentially deploying the application to the other space. You can switch to the integration space and then deploy the same application. You can use blue green deployment to accomplish this.', '', 30, 1, 0, 0, 103, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(169, 'What authentication techniques are supported in Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'User Account and Authentication (UAA) is the central identity management service for the Atos Cloud Foundry platform and its various components. UAA acts as an OAuth2 Authorization Server and issues access tokens for applications that request platform resources. The tokens are based on the JSON Web Token and are digitally signed by UAA.\r\n\r\nApplications that users deploy to Atos Cloud Foundry exist within a space. Spaces exist within orgs. To view and access an org or a space, a user must be a member of it. Cloud Foundry uses role-based access control (RBAC), where, each role is granted permissions to either an org or a specified space.\r\n\r\nThe different access roles available in Atos Cloud Foundry are:\r\n\r\n<strong>Org Manager</strong>\r\n\r\nAssign this role to managers or other users who need to administer the account.\r\n\r\nAn Org Manager can do the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Add and manage users</li>\r\n 	<li>View users and edit org roles</li>\r\n 	<li>View the org quota</li>\r\n 	<li>Create, view, edit, and delete spaces</li>\r\n 	<li>Invite and manage users in spaces</li>\r\n 	<li>View the status, number of instances, service bindings, and resource use of each application in every space in the org</li>\r\n 	<li>Add domains</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Org Auditor</strong>\r\n\r\nAssign this role to people who need to view but not edit user information and org quota usage information.\r\n\r\nAn Org Auditor can do the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>View users and org roles</li>\r\n 	<li>View the org quota</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Billing Manager</strong>\r\n\r\nAssign this role to people who need to create and manage billing account and payment information.\r\n\r\nA Billing Manager can do the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Set the org spending limit</li>\r\n 	<li>Create and set payment information</li>\r\n 	<li>Read invoices and payment history</li>\r\n 	<li>Create and edit the invoice notification email addresses</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Space Manager</strong>\r\n\r\nAssign this role to managers or other users who need to administer a space.\r\n\r\nA Space Manager can do the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Add and manage users in the space</li>\r\n 	<li>View the status, number of instances, service bindings, and resource use of each application in the space</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Space Developer</strong>\r\n\r\nAssign this role to application developers or other users who need to manage applications and services in a space.\r\n\r\nA Space Developer can do the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Deploy an application</li>\r\n 	<li>Start or stop an application</li>\r\n 	<li>Rename an application</li>\r\n 	<li>Delete an application</li>\r\n 	<li>Create, view, edit, and delete services in a space</li>\r\n 	<li>Bind or unbind a service to an application</li>\r\n 	<li>Rename a space</li>\r\n 	<li>View the status, number of instances, service bindings, and resource use of each application in the space</li>\r\n 	<li>Change the number of instances, memory allocation, and disk limit of each application in the space</li>\r\n 	<li>Associate an internal or external URL with an application</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Space Auditor</strong>\r\n\r\nAssign this role to people who need to view but not edit the space.\r\n\r\nA Space Auditor can do the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>View the status, number of instances, service bindings, and resource use of each application in the space</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 31, 1, 0, 0, 107, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(172, 'How can I run non-web application in Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, '<blockquote>cf push &lt;app_name&gt; --no-route</blockquote>', '', 32, 1, 0, 0, 105, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(178, 'What are the security measures available in Atos Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'Auditing, Firewall rules, OS Hardening, Vulnerability Scans, Patch Management, RBAC (Role Based Access Control), TLS/SSL Certificates are the security measures available in Atos Cloud Foundry.', '', 33, 1, 0, 0, 107, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(181, 'How can I connect to my own existing service and application running in Cloud Foundry?', 1, 'The CF CLI lets you securely log into remote host VMs running Cloud Foundry application instances. A cloud operator can deploy Cloud Foundry to either allow or prohibit Application SSH across the entire deployment.\r\n\r\nThere are two ways of SSH to CF system:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Configuring SSH Access at the Application Level - Enables SSH access to all instances of an app<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-328" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/faq/sshAccessApp.png" alt="" width="343" height="43" /></li>\r\n 	<li>Configuring SSH Access at the Space Level - Allows SSH access into all apps in a space<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-331" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/faq/sshAccessSpace.png" alt="" width="309" height="39" /></li>\r\n 	<li>Logging Into an Application Container with CF SSH</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf SSH access is allowed at the deployment, space, and application level, you can run “CF SSH APP-NAME” from the CF CLI to start an interactive SSH session with a VM hosting an application\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-334" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/faq/sshAccessDeploy.png" alt="" width="293" height="39" /></li></ul>', '', 34, 1, 0, 0, 113, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(187, 'About LDAP: How can I integrate the CF to LDAP to my company’s LDAP?', 1, 'The Cloud Foundry UAA supports integration with an external LDAP server for authentication. If the credentials for this LDAP server are provided, we can deploy CF with this integration and your users can sign in with their existing credentials.\r\n\r\nNetwork domain: How to manage it consistently with my current domain names?', '', 35, 1, 0, 0, 104, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(190, 'VPN / SSH: how to secure the connectivity to CF and CF-Apps? ', 1, 'Use a BOSH release that enforces IPSEC communication between BOSH deployed systems. Deployed on VMs alongside CF components, it transparently encrypts all traffic in transit.\r\n\r\nNo CF code changes are necessary, just a co-located IPSEC release alongside CF, and a customized deployment manifest.\r\n\r\nAn IPSEC policy is added for each member that is participating in the IPSEC mesh. This makes it possible to be selective about what is protected, as well as keeping traffic to unrelated systems (DNS, log servers, etc.) unencrypted.\r\n\r\nAn IKE daemon is used to rotate the encryption keys on a user defined schedule. The exact encryption policies are configurable through the BOSH manifest.', '', 36, 1, 0, 0, 105, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(196, 'How 2 different apps can communicate / cooperate with one another?', 1, 'One way to achieve such requirements in ACF is by using a messaging service (like RabbitMQ) to communicate between instances of applications. You can also store shared information in a database service or any remote location outside the file system.', '', 37, 1, 0, 0, 108, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(202, 'Installing CF CLI on Windows', 4, '<strong>Procedure</strong>\r\n\r\nTo install the CF CLI on Windows, follow the steps below:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Download and unzip MSI installer package.\r\n<a href="https://cli.run.pivotal.io/stable?release=windows32">Windows 32 bit</a> Or <a href="https://cli.run.pivotal.io/stable?release=windows64">Windows 64 bit</a></li>\r\n 	<li>Double-click the CF CLI executable file.</li>\r\n 	<li>When prompted, click <strong>Install</strong>, and follow the screen instructions (for example, click <strong>Next</strong>).</li>\r\n 	<li>After successful installation, click <strong>Close</strong>.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Next step</strong>\r\n\r\nTo verify installation, open a terminal window and type <strong>cf</strong>.\r\n\r\nIf the installation is successful, system displays the CF CLI help listing.', '', 38, 1, 0, 0, 100, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(205, 'Installing CF CLI on Linux', 4, '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Procedure</strong>\r\n\r\nTo install the CF CLI on Linux, follow the steps below:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Download the CF CLI package from the CLI releases page -<a href="https://github.com/cloudfoundry/cli/releases">https://github.com/cloudfoundry/cli/releases</a></li>\r\n 	<li>Install using system package manager.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Note</strong>: These commands may require <em>sudo</em>.\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Debian/Ubuntu:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<blockquote>dpkg -i path/to/cf-cli-*.deb &amp;&amp; apt-get install –f</blockquote>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li style="list-style-type: none">\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>Red Hat:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<blockquote>rpm -i path/to/cf-cli-*.rpm</blockquote>\r\n<strong>Next Step </strong>\r\n\r\nTo verify your installation, open a terminal window and type cf.\r\n\r\nIf your installation is successful, system displays the CF CLI help listing.', '', 39, 1, 0, 0, 86, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(208, 'Install CF CLI on Mac OS X', 4, '<strong>Procedure</strong>\r\n\r\nTo install the CF CLI on Mac OS X, follow the steps below:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Download the CF CLI for <a href="https://cli.run.pivotal.io/stable?release=macosx64">Mac OS X 64 bit</a></li>\r\n 	<li>Open the <em>.pkg</em> The Installer wizard appears.</li>\r\n 	<li>Click <strong>Continue</strong> to install the file.</li>\r\n 	<li>Select a destination folder for file installation and click <strong>Continue</strong>.</li>\r\n 	<li>When prompted, click <strong>Install</strong>, and follow the screen instructions (for example, click <strong>Next</strong>.).</li>\r\n 	<li>After successful installation, click <strong>Close</strong>.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Next Step</strong>\r\n\r\nTo verify installation, open a terminal window and type cf.\r\n\r\nIf the installation is successful, system displays the CF CLI help listing.', '', 40, 1, 0, 0, 79, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(211, 'Uninstalling the CF CLI on Windows OS', 4, '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Procedure</strong>\r\n\r\nTo uninstall the CF Command Line Interface from Windows OS 7 and above, follow the instructions below:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Navigate to the <strong>Control Panel</strong>.</li>\r\n 	<li>Click <strong>Programs and Features</strong>.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nA list of the programs or software with installation date and version is displayed.\r\n<ol start="3">\r\n 	<li>Select <em>Cloud Foundry CLI VERSION</em> and click <strong>Uninstall</strong>.</li>\r\n 	<li>After uninstallation, click <strong>OK</strong>.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nAlternate method to launch Programs and Features menu from the command line with the following command:\r\n<blockquote>  appwiz.cpl</blockquote>', '', 41, 1, 0, 0, 77, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(214, 'Uninstall CF CLI on Mac OS X', 4, '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Procedure</strong>\r\n\r\nTo uninstall the CF Command Line Interface from Mac OS X and above, follow the instructions below:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li>Open the folder <strong>binary</strong>.</li>\r\n 	<li>Under binary, delete the <strong>binary /usr/local/bin/cf</strong></li>\r\n 	<li>Under directory, delete <strong>Directory /usr/local/share/doc/cf-cli</strong></li>\r\n</ol>', '', 42, 1, 0, 0, 72, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(217, 'Uninstall CF CLI on Linux', 4, '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Procedure</strong>\r\n\r\nTo uninstall the CF Command Line Interface from Linux, follow the instructions below:\r\n\r\nRun the following command to uninstall the CF CLI using pip.\r\n<blockquote>$ sudo pip uninstall CF-cli</blockquote>', '', 43, 1, 0, 0, 72, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(220, 'Command Structure in the CF-CLI', 4, 'The CF-CLI is a multipart string on the command line, as shown below:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf &lt;command&gt; &lt;subcommand&gt; [options and parameters]</blockquote>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>It begins with the base call to <em>cf</em>.</li>\r\n 	<li>The first part indicates a top-level command, which often represents a CF service supported in the CF-CLI.</li>\r\n 	<li>The top-level command (CF service) can have additional subcommands, which often represents the specific operation.</li>\r\n 	<li>Whereas, the general CLI options and operation parameters are specified on the command line in any order.</li>\r\n 	<li>If an exclusive parameter is repeated several times, then only the <em>last value</em></li>\r\n 	<li>Options and Parameters can take various types of input values, such as Orgs and Spaces.</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 44, 1, 0, 0, 81, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(223, 'Help', 4, '<p class="Section">Purpose:</p>\r\n<p class="Normal1"><span lang="EN-US">Use this command to view the help content on CF-CLI.</span></p>\r\n<p class="Section">Syntax:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>$ cf --help</blockquote>\r\n<img class="size-full wp-image-136 alignnone" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/1-2.png" alt="" width="717" height="322" />\r\n', '', 45, 1, 0, 0, 81, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(226, 'Login', 4, '<p class="Section">Purpose:</p>\r\n<p class="Normal1"><span lang="EN-US">Use the command to log in to the cloud foundry server. The system connects with the server only if you have right to access it. If you do not have sufficient access rights, the system displays the error message. When you enter the command, the system asks for API. However, if the API is already set, the system would ask for the user email and password.</span></p>\r\n<p class="Section">Syntax:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>$ cf login</blockquote>\r\n<img class=" wp-image-139 alignnone" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/2-1.png" alt="" width="486" height="143" />', '', 46, 1, 0, 0, 90, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(229, 'Password', 4, '<p class="Section">Purpose:</p>\r\n<p class="Normal1"><span lang="EN-US">Use this command to change the user password post login  </span></p>\r\n<p class="Section">Syntax:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>$ cf passwd</blockquote>\r\n<p class="Section">Example:</p>\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-142" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/3-1.png" alt="" width="396" height="19" />', '', 47, 1, 0, 0, 80, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(232, 'Logout', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse the command to logout of the cloud foundry server .\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf logout</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-145" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/4-1.png" alt="" width="398" height="51" />', '', 48, 1, 0, 0, 80, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(235, 'Target', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to access or redirect to the targeted object (for example <em>org</em> or <em>space)</em> and view its details.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf target -o &lt;org name&gt;</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>$ cf target -o &lt;org name&gt; -s &lt;space name&gt;</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-148" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/5.png" alt="" width="973" height="193" />', '', 49, 1, 0, 0, 83, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(238, 'API', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to navigate or redirect to the targeted API URL and view corresponding details.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf target &lt;API URL&gt;</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-151" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/6.png" alt="" width="873" height="46" />', '', 50, 1, 0, 0, 81, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(241, 'Authentication', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to authenticate or validate user interactivity with the system.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf auth</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-154" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/7.png" alt="" width="943" height="227" />', '', 51, 1, 0, 0, 76, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(244, 'Applications', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to  list of all available applications.\r\n\r\n<em>Note :- The user must be targeted to an org and space to list the applications</em>\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf apps</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-157" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/8.png" alt="" width="626" height="136" />', '', 52, 1, 0, 0, 84, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(247, 'Application health', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view health and status for an application.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf app APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-160" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/9.png" alt="" width="663" height="236" />', '', 53, 1, 0, 0, 82, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(250, 'Push', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to Push a new app or sync changes to an existing app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf push APP_NAME –b BUILDPACK_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-163" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/10.png" alt="" width="1065" height="354" />', '', 54, 1, 0, 0, 85, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(253, 'Scale', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to Change or view the instance count, hard-disk space limit, and memory limit for an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf scale APP_NAME [-i INSTANCES] [-k DISK] [-m MEMORY] [-f]</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-166" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/11.png" alt="" width="958" height="449" />', '', 55, 1, 0, 0, 75, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(256, 'Delete', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf delete APP_NAME [-f -r]</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-169" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/12.png" alt="" width="986" height="189" />', '', 56, 1, 0, 0, 74, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(259, 'Rename', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to rename an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf rename APP_NAME NEW_APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-172" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/13.png" alt="" width="931" height="75" />', '', 57, 1, 0, 0, 72, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(262, 'Start', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to start an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf start APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-175" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/14.png" alt="" width="840" height="466" />', '', 58, 1, 0, 0, 76, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(265, 'Stop', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to stop or close an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf stop APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-178" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/15.png" alt="" width="788" height="76" />', '', 59, 1, 0, 0, 71, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(268, 'Restart', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to restart the app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf restart APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-181" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/16.png" alt="" width="814" height="487" />', '', 60, 1, 0, 0, 75, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(271, 'Restage', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to restage the app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf restage APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-184" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/17.png" alt="" width="1236" height="441" />', '', 61, 1, 0, 0, 73, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(274, 'Restart App Instance', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to restart a particular instance of an application\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf restart-app-instance APP_NAME INDEX</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-187" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/18.png" alt="" width="1359" height="110" />', '', 62, 1, 0, 0, 76, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(277, 'Events', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view recent app events.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf events APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-190" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/19.png" alt="" width="1332" height="201" />', '', 63, 1, 0, 0, 76, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(280, 'Logs', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view recent logs for an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf logs APP_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-193" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/20.png" alt="" width="711" height="164" />\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<img class="alignnone  wp-image-196" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/21.png" alt="" width="712" height="173" />', '', 64, 1, 0, 0, 75, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(283, 'Environment', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view all environment variables for an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf env APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-199" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/22.png" alt="" width="837" height="570" />', '', 65, 1, 0, 0, 76, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(286, 'Set Environment', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to set (configure) an environment variable for an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf set-env APP_NAME ENV_VAR_NAME ENV_VAR_VALUE</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-202" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/23.png" alt="" width="1542" height="112" />', '', 66, 1, 0, 0, 75, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(289, 'Unset Environment', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to remove an environment variable for an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf unset-env APP_NAME ENV_VAR_NAME ENV_VAR_VALUE</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-205" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/24.png" alt="" width="1221" height="118" />', '', 67, 1, 0, 0, 73, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(292, 'Stacks', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view the list of all stacks. A stack is a pre-built file system, including an operating system that can run apps.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf stacks</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-208" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/25.png" alt="" width="1063" height="276" />', '', 68, 1, 0, 0, 76, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(295, 'Stack', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view information for a stack.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf stack STACK_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-211" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/26.png" alt="" width="1277" height="260" />', '', 69, 1, 0, 0, 75, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(298, 'Copy Source', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to copy the app source code from one application to another. Unless overridden, the copy-source command will restart the application.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf copy-source SOURCE-APP TARGET-APP [-S TARGET-SPACE [-O TARGET-ORG]] [--no-restart]</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>-S </strong>stands for the Space that contains the targeted application</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>- O </strong>stands for the Org that contains the targeted application</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>--no </strong>stands for Override restart of the application in the targeted environment when copy-source completes</li>\r\n</ul>', '', 70, 1, 0, 0, 75, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(301, 'Create App Manifest', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create an app manifest for the app that has been pushed successfully.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf create-app-manifest APP_NAME [-p /path/to/&lt;app-name&gt;-manifest.yml]</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>-<strong>p </strong>specifies a path for file creation. If path is not specified, manifest file is created in current working directory.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-217" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/28.png" alt="" width="1524" height="229" />', '', 71, 1, 0, 0, 74, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(304, 'Get Health Check', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to get the health_check_type value of an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf get-health-check APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-220" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/29.png" alt="" width="1353" height="176" />', '', 72, 1, 0, 0, 74, 'admin', '14-07-2017');
INSERT INTO `wp_spider_faq_question` (`id`, `title`, `category`, `article`, `fullarticle`, `ordering`, `published`, `like`, `unlike`, `hits`, `user_name`, `date`) VALUES
(307, 'Set Health Check', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to set health_check_type flag to either <em>port</em> or <em>none</em>.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf set-health-check APP_NAME (process | port | http [--endpoint PATH])</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>--endpoint</strong> specifies the path on the app (Default: /)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-223" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/30.png" alt="" width="1342" height="172" />', '', 73, 1, 0, 0, 71, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(310, 'Enable SSH', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to enable SSH for the application.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf enable-ssh APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-226" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/31.png" alt="" width="993" height="162" />', '', 74, 1, 0, 0, 73, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(313, 'Disable SSH', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to disable SSH for the application.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n\r\n$ cf disable-ssh APP_NAME\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-229" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/32.png" alt="" width="1002" height="157" />', '', 75, 1, 0, 0, 70, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(316, 'SSH Enabled', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view whether SSH is enabled on an application container instance.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf ssh-enabled APP_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-232" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/33.png" alt="" width="1010" height="138" />', '', 76, 1, 0, 0, 72, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(319, 'SSH', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to connect SSH to an application container instance.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf ssh APP_NAME [-i app-instance-index] [-c Command] [-L (bind address:)port:host:hostport] [--skip-host-validation] [--skip-remote-execution] [--request-pseudo-tty] [--force-pseudo-tty] [--disable-pseudo-tty]</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>--app-instance-index, -i</strong> stands for application instance index (Default: 0)</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>--command, -c</strong> stands for command to run. This flag can be defined more than once.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>--disable-pseudo-tty, -T</strong> stands for disable pseudo-tty allocation</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>--force-pseudo-tty</strong> stands for force pseudo-tty allocation</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>-L</strong> stands for local port forward specification. This flag can be defined more than once.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>--request-pseudo-tty, -t</strong> stands for request pseudo-tty allocation</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>--skip-host-validation, -k</strong> stands for skip host key validation</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>--skip-remote-execution, -N</strong> - Do not execute a remote command</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-235" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/34.png" alt="" width="876" height="80" />', '', 77, 1, 0, 0, 73, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(322, 'Marketplace', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of available offerings in the marketplace.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf marketplace</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-238" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/35.png" alt="" width="950" height="476" />', '', 78, 1, 0, 0, 78, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(325, 'Services', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of available service instances.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf services</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-241" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/36.png" alt="" width="1330" height="212" />', '', 79, 1, 0, 0, 76, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(328, 'Service', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view health of the running service instances.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf service &lt;service-instance-name&gt;</blockquote>\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-496" src="https://faq.apps.eu01.cf.canopy-cloud.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/2019-05-17-17_01_00-.png" alt="" width="1036" height="304" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '', 80, 1, 0, 0, 77, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(331, 'Create Service', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create new service instances.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf create-service &lt;SERVICE_NAME&gt;&lt;PLAN_NAME&gt;&lt;SERVICE_INSTANCE_NAME&gt;</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-247" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/38.png" alt="" width="1301" height="351" />', '', 81, 1, 0, 0, 75, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(334, 'Update Service', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command toupdate service instances.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf update-service SERVICE_INSTANCE [-p NEW_PLAN] [-c PARAMETERS_AS_JSON] [-t TAGS]</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>-c</strong> stands for valid JSON object containing service-specific configuration parameters, provided either in-line or in a file. For a list of supported configuration parameters, see documentation for the particular service offering.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>-p</strong> stands for change service plan for a service instance</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>-t</strong> stands for user provided tags</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-250" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/39.png" alt="" width="746" height="108" />', '', 82, 1, 0, 0, 73, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(337, 'Delete Service ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete service instances.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf delete-service SERVICE_INSTANCE [-f]</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>-f</strong> stands for force deletion without confirmation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-253" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/40.png" alt="" width="812" height="374" />', '', 83, 1, 0, 0, 73, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(340, 'Rename Service', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to rename service instances.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf rename-service OLD_SERVICE_INSTANCE_NAME NEW_SERVICE_INSTANCE_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-256" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/41.png" alt="" width="1239" height="256" />', '', 84, 1, 0, 0, 70, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(343, 'Create Service Key', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create key for service instances.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf create-service-key SERVICE_INSTANCE SERVICE_KEY -c PATH_TO_FILE/ JSON PARAMETERS</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>-c</strong> stands for valid JSON object containing service-specific configuration parameters, provided either in-line or in a file. For a list of supported configuration parameters, see documentation for the particular service offering.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-259" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/42.png" alt="" width="1362" height="98" />\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-262" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/43.png" alt="" width="1473" height="86" />', '', 85, 1, 0, 0, 72, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(346, 'Service Keys', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view the list of keys available for a service instance.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf service-keys SERVICE_INSTANCE</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-265" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/44.png" alt="" width="887" height="169" />', '', 86, 1, 0, 0, 71, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(349, 'Service Key', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view service key information.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf service-key SERVICE_INSTANCE SERVICE_KEY</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-268" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/45.png" alt="" width="990" height="222" />', '', 87, 1, 0, 0, 72, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(352, 'Delete Service Key', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete a service key.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf delete-service-key SERVICE_INSTANCE SERVICE_KEY [-f]</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>-f stands for force deletion without confirmation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-271" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/46.png" alt="" width="1246" height="172" />', '', 88, 1, 0, 0, 72, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(355, 'Bind Service', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to bind a service instance to an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf bind-service &lt;APP-NAME&gt;&lt;SERVICE_INSTANCE_NAME&gt;</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-274" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/47.png" alt="" width="884" height="83" />', '', 89, 1, 0, 0, 72, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(358, 'Unbind Service', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to unbind a service instance to an app.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf unbind-service &lt;APP-NAME&gt;&lt;SERVICE_INSTANCE_NAME&gt;</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-277" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/48.png" alt="" width="900" height="75" />', '', 90, 1, 0, 0, 71, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(361, 'Create User Provided Service', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to make a user-provided service instance available to cf apps.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf create-user-provided-service SERVICE_INSTANCE -p PATH_TO_FILE</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>-p stands for credentials, provided inline or in a file, to be exposed in the VCAP_SERVICES environment variable for bound applications.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-280" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/49.png" alt="" width="593" height="37" />\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-283" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/50.png" alt="" width="1145" height="82" />\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-286" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/51.png" alt="" width="1133" height="127" />', '', 91, 1, 0, 0, 73, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(364, 'Update User Provided Service', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to update user-provided service instance name value pairs.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf update-user-provided-service SERVICE_INSTANCE -p PATH_TO_FILE</blockquote>\r\nWhere,\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>-p stands for credentials, provided inline or in a file, to be exposed in the VCAP_SERVICES environment variable for bound applications.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-289" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/52.png" alt="" width="1174" height="85" />', '', 92, 1, 0, 0, 70, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(367, 'Orgs', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view the list of all orgs.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf orgs</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-292" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/53.png" alt="" width="627" height="233" />', '', 93, 1, 0, 0, 76, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(370, 'Org', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view org info.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf org</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-295" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/54.png" alt="" width="875" height="174" />', '', 94, 1, 0, 0, 74, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(373, 'Create Org', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create an org with specified name.\r\n\r\nUse <em>cf target –o ORG_NAME</em> to target newly created org.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf create-org ORG_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-298" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/55.png" alt="" width="744" height="200" />', '', 95, 1, 0, 0, 72, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(376, 'Delete Org', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete an org with specified name.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>$ cf delete-org ORG_NAME</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-301" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/56.png" alt="" width="887" height="336" />', '', 96, 1, 0, 0, 71, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(379, 'Rename Org', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to rename an org with specified name.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf rename-org ORG_NAME NEW_ORG_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/57.png" alt="" width="534" height="317" />', '', 97, 1, 0, 0, 74, 'admin', '14-07-2017'),
(381, 'New question', 8, 'testing ', '', 98, 1, 0, 0, 1, 'suchita', '22-03-2018'),
(382, 'Spaces', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view the list all spaces in an org.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf spaces</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/58.png" alt="" width="511" height="126" />', '', 99, 1, 0, 0, 18, 'suchita', '02-04-2018'),
(383, 'Space', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view space information.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf space SPACE_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/59.png" alt="" width="1006" height="228" />', '', 100, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(384, 'Create Space', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create a new space.\r\n  First target an org before creating a new space. For example, $ cf target –o ORG_NAME \r\n  Use ‘cf target –o ORG_NAME –s SPACE_NAME’ to target newly created space.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-space SPACE_NAME [-o ORG] [-q SPACE_QUOTA]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>-o stands for organization\r\n	-q stands for quota to assign to the newly created space</ol>\r\n\r\n\r\n', '', 101, 1, 0, 0, 18, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(385, 'Delete Space ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete an existing space. The system asks for confirmation to delete the space. Type yes to delete it permanently. Type no to cancel the action.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-space SPACE_NAME [-o ORG] [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>-f stands for force deletion without confirmation.\r\n	-o stands for deleting space within specified org.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/60.png" alt="" width="794" height="228" />', '', 102, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(386, 'Rename Space', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to rename an existing space.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf rename-space SPACE_NAME NEW_SPACE_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/61.png" alt="" width="684" height="293" />', '', 103, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(387, 'Allow Space SSH', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to allow the SSH access for the space.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf allow-space-ssh SPACE_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/62.png" alt="" width="724" height="111" />', '', 104, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(388, 'Disallow Space SSH', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to restrict the SSH access for the space.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf disallow-space-ssh SPACE_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/63.png" alt="" width="745" height="105" />', '', 105, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(389, 'Space SSH Allowed', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to report whether SSH is allowed in a space or not.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf space-ssh-allowed SPACE_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/64.png" alt="" width="767" height="78" />', '', 106, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(390, 'Domains', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view the list of domains in the target org.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf domains</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/65.png" alt="" width="567" height="110" />', '', 107, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(391, 'Create Domain', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create a new domain in an org.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-domain ORG DOMAIN</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/66.png" alt="" width="1148" height="403" />', '', 108, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(392, 'Delete Domain', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete an existing domain from an org.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-domain DOMAIN [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>-f stands for force deletion of the targeted domain without confirmation or warning.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/67.png" alt="" width="1077" height="93" />', '', 109, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(393, 'Create Shared Domain', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create a new domain that can be used by all orgs. Only administrator can create this type of domains.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-shared-domain DOMAIN [--router-group ROUTER_GROUP]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>--router-group means routes for this domain will be configured only on the specified router group</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/68.png" alt="" width="1142" height="78" />', '', 110, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(394, 'Delete Shared Domain', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete an existing shared domain. Only administrator can delete this type of domains.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-shared-domain DOMAIN [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>-f stands for force deletion of the targeted shared domain without confirmation or warning.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/69.png" alt="" width="922" height="88" />', '', 111, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(395, 'Routes', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of all routes in the targeted space and organization.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf routes [--orglevel]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>--orglevel list all the routes for all spaces of current organization.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/70.png" alt="" width="1007" height="119" />', '', 112, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(396, 'Create Route ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create a new URL route in a space.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-route SPACE DOMAIN [--hostname HOSTNAME] [--path PATH]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-route SPACE DOMAIN [--port PORT] [--random PORT]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>--hostname, -n stands for hostname for the HTTP route (required for shared domains)\r\n	--path stands for path for the HTTP route\r\n	--port stands for port for the TCP route\r\n	--random-port creates a random port for the TCP route</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/71.png" alt="" width="1141" height="80" />', '', 113, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(397, 'Check Route', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create a new URL route in a space.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf check-route HOST DOMAIN [--path PATH]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>--path stands for the path for the targeted route.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/72.png" alt="" width="1017" height="109" />', '', 114, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(398, 'Map Route', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to add a URL route to an application.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf map-route APP_NAME DOMAIN [--hostname HOSTNAME] [--path PATH]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf map-route APP_NAME DOMAIN [--port PORT] [--random PORT]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>--hostname, -n stands for hostname for the HTTP route (required for shared domains)\r\n	--path stands for path for the HTTP route\r\n	--port stands for port for the TCP route\r\n	--random-port creates a random port for the TCP route</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/73.png" alt="" width="1165" height="136" />', '', 115, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(399, 'Unmap Route', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to remove a URL route linked to any application.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf unmap-route APP_NAME DOMAIN [--hostname HOSTNAME] [--path PATH]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf unmap-route APP_NAME DOMAIN [--port PORT] [--random PORT]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/74.png" alt="" width="1168" height="78" />', '', 116, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(400, 'Delete Route', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete a URL route linked to any application.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-route APP_NAME DOMAIN [--hostname HOSTNAME] [--path PATH]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-route APP_NAME DOMAIN [--port PORT] [--random PORT]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/75.png" alt="" width="1158" height="91" />', '', 117, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(401, 'Delete Orphaned Routes', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to forcefully delete all orphaned routes that are not mapped to apps.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-orphaned-routes [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>-f stands for force deletion of the targeted shared domain without confirmation or warning.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/76.png" alt="" width="735" height="129" />', '', 118, 1, 0, 0, 18, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(402, 'Router Groups', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of all router groups.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf router-groups</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/77.png" alt="" width="617" height="132" />', '', 119, 1, 0, 0, 17, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(403, 'Buildpacks', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view the list of all buildpacks.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf buildpacks</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/78.png" alt="" width="960" height="338" />', '', 120, 1, 0, 0, 17, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(404, 'Create Buildpack', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create a new buildpack.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-buildpack BUILDPACK PATH POSITION [--enable|--disable]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>--disable stands for disable the buildpack from being used for staging\r\n	--enable  stands for enable the buildpack to be used for staging</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/79.png" alt="" width="1185" height="515" />', '', 121, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(405, 'Update Buildpack', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to update a buildpack.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf update-buildpack BUILDPACK [-p PATH] [-i POSITION] [--enable|--disable] [--lock|--unlock]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>--disable stands for disable the buildpack from being used for staging\r\n	--enable  stands for enable the buildpack to be used for staging\r\n	-i stands for the order in which the buildpacks are checked during buildpack auto-detection\r\n	--lock stands for locking the buildpack to prevent updates\r\n	-p stands for path to directory or zip file\r\n	--unlock stands for unlocking the buildpack to enable updates</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/80.png" alt="" width="814" height="93" />', '', 122, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(406, 'Rename Buildpack', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to rename a buildpack.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf rename-buildpack BUILDPACK_NAME NEW_BUILDPACK_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/81.png" alt="" width="822" height="97" />', '', 123, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(407, 'Delete-Buildpack', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete a buildpack.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-buildpack BUILDPACK [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>-f stands for force deletion of the targeted buildpack without confirmation or warning.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/82.png" alt="" width="732" height="93" />', '', 124, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(408, 'Create User', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create a new user.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-user USERNAME PASSWORD</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/83.png" alt="" width="837" height="217" />', '', 125, 1, 0, 0, 17, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(409, 'Delete User', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete an existing user.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-user USERNAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-502" src="https://faq.apps.eu01.cf.canopy-cloud.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/2019-05-17-17_34_55-Window.png" alt="" width="396" height="162" />', '', 126, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(410, 'Org Users', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view org users by role.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf org-users ORG_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/85.png" alt="" width="531" height="264" />', '', 127, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(411, 'Set Org Role', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to assign an org role to a user.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf set-org-role USERNAME ORG ROLE</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\nORG ROLE can be – \r\n	<ol>OrgManager - Invite and manage users, select and change plans, and set spending limits\r\n	BillingManager - Create and manage the billing account and payment info\r\n	OrgAuditor - Read-only access to org info and reports</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/86.png" alt="" width="1033" height="89" />', '', 128, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(412, 'Unset Org Role', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to remove an org role of a user.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf unset-org-role USERNAME ORG ROLE</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\nORG ROLE can be – \r\n	<ol>OrgManager - Invite and manage users, select and change plans, and set spending limits\r\n	BillingManager - Create and manage the billing account and payment info\r\n	OrgAuditor - Read-only access to org info and reports</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/87.png" alt="" width="992" height="82" />', '', 129, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(413, 'Space Users', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view space users by role.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf space-users ORG_NAME SPACE_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/88.png" alt="" width="678" height="282" />', '', 130, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(414, 'Set Space Role', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to assign a space role to a user.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf set-space-role USERNAME ORG_NAME SPACE_NAME SPACE_ROLE</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\nSPACE ROLE can be – \r\n	<ol>SpaceManager - Invite and manage users, and enable features for a given space\r\n	SpaceDeveloper - Create and manage apps and services, and see logs and reports\r\n	SpaceAuditor - View logs, reports, and settings on this space</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/89.png" alt="" width="1151" height="83" />', '', 131, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(415, 'Unset Space Role', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to remove a space role to a user.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf unset-space-role USERNAME ORG_NAME SPACE_NAME SPACE_ROLE</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\nSPACE ROLE  can be – \r\n	<ol>SpaceManager - Invite and manage users, and enable features for a given space\r\n	SpaceDeveloper - Create and manage apps and services, and see logs and reports\r\n	SpaceAuditor - View logs, reports, and settings on this space</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/90.png" alt="" width="1121" height="87" />', '', 132, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '03-04-2018'),
(416, 'Quotas', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of the entire available usage quotas.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf quotas</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/91.png" alt="" width="1143" height="132" />', '', 133, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(417, 'Quota', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view quota related information.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf quota QUOTA</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/92.png" alt="" width="508" height="267" />', '', 134, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(418, 'Set Quota', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to assign a quota to an org.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf set-quota ORG QUOTA</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/93.png" alt="" width="589" height="88" />', '', 135, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(419, 'Create Quota', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to define a new resource quota.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-quota QUOTA [-m TOTAL_MEMORY] [-i INSTANCE_MEMORY] [-r ROUTES] [-s SERVICE_INSTANCES] [-a APP_INSTANCES] [--allow-paid-service-plans] [--reserved-route-ports RESERVED_ROUTE_PORTS]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>\r\n-a stands for total number of application instances. -1 represents an unlimited amount. (Default: unlimited)\r\n	--allow-paid-service-plans can provision instances of paid service plans\r\n	-i stands for maximum amount of memory an application instance can have (e.g. 1024M, 1G, 10G). -1 represents an unlimited amount.\r\n	-m stands for total amount of memory a space can have (e.g. 1024M, 1G, 10G)\r\n	-r stands for total number of routes\r\n	--reserved-route-ports provides maximum number of routes that may be created with reserved ports (Default: 0)\r\n	-s stands for total number of service instances</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/94.png" alt="" width="1181" height="82" />', '', 136, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(420, 'Delete Quota ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete the existing quota.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-quota QUOTA [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n   <ol>	-f stands for force deletion of the targeted quota without confirmation or warning.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/95.png" alt="" width="610" height="78" />', '', 137, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(421, 'Update Quota', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to update an existing resource quota.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf update-quota QUOTA [-m TOTAL_MEMORY] [-i INSTANCE_MEMORY] [-n NEW_NAME] [-r ROUTES] [-s SERVICE_INSTANCES] [-a APP_INSTANCES] [--allow-paid-service-plans | --disallow-paid-service-plans] [--reserved-route-ports RESERVED_ROUTE_PORTS]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n   <ol>-a stands for total number of application instances. -1 represents an unlimited amount.\r\n	--allow-paid-service-plans can provision instances of paid service plans\r\n	--disallow-paid-service-plans cannot provision instances of paid service plans\r\n	-i stands for maximum amount of memory an application instance can have (e.g. 1024M, 1G, 10G)\r\n	-m stands for total amount of memory (e.g. 1024M, 1G, 10G)\r\n	-n stands for new name\r\n	-r stands for total number of routes\r\n	--reserved-route-ports stands for maximum number of routes that may be created with reserved ports\r\n	-s stands for total number of service instances</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/96.png" alt="" width="1180" height="83" />', '', 138, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(422, 'Share Private Domain', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to Share a private domain with an org.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf share-private-domain ORG_NAME DOMAIN_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/97.png" alt="" width="721" height="83" />', '', 139, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(423, 'Unshare Private Domain', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to remove sharing of a private domain with an org.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf unshare-private-domain ORG_NAME DOMAIN_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/98.png" alt="" width="828" height="89" />', '', 140, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(424, 'Space Quotas', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view the list of all the available space resource quotas.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf space-quotas</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/99.png" alt="" width="1353" height="162" />', '', 141, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(425, 'Space Quota', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view the space quota related information.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf space-quota SPACE_QUOTA_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/100.png" alt="" width="633" height="319" />', '', 142, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(426, 'Create Space Quota', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to define a new space resource quota.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-space-quota QUOTA [-i INSTANCE_MEMORY] [-m MEMORY] [-r ROUTES] [-s SERVICE_INSTANCES] [-a APP_INSTANCES] [--allow-paid-service-plans] [--reserved-route-ports RESERVED_ROUTE_PORTS]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>\r\n-a stands for total number of application instances. -1 represents an unlimited amount. (Default: unlimited)\r\n	--allow-paid-service-plans can provision instances of paid service plans (Default: disallowed)\r\n	-i stands for maximum amount of memory an application instance can have (e.g. 1024M, 1G, 10G). -1 represents an unlimited amount. (Default: unlimited)\r\n	-m stands for total amount of memory a space can have (e.g. 1024M, 1G, 10G)\r\n	-r stands for total number of routes\r\n	--reserved-route-ports stands for maximum number of routes that may be created with reserved ports (Default: 0)\r\n	-s stands for total number of service instances</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/101.png" alt="" width="1479" height="101" />', '', 143, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(427, 'Update Space Quota', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to update an existing space quota.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf update-space-quota SPACE_QUOTA [-i INSTANCE_MEMORY] [-m MEMORY] [-n NAME] [-r ROUTES] [-s SERVICE_INSTANCES] [-a APP_INSTANCES] [--allow-paid-service-plans | --disallow-paid-service-plans] [--reserved-route-ports RESERVED_ROUTE_PORTS]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n\r\n	<ol>\r\n	-a stands for total number of application instances. -1 represents an unlimited amount. (Default: unlimited)\r\n	--allow-paid-service-plans can provision instances of paid service plans (Default: disallowed)\r\n	-i stands for maximum amount of memory an application instance can have (e.g. 1024M, 1G, 10G). -1 represents an unlimited amount. (Default: unlimited)\r\n	-m stands for total amount of memory a space can have (e.g. 1024M, 1G, 10G)\r\n	-r stands for total number of routes\r\n	-n stands for new name\r\n	-r stands for total number of routes\r\n	--reserved-route-ports stands for maximum number of routes that may be created with reserved ports (Default: 0)\r\n	-s stands for total number of service instances </ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/102.png" alt="" width="1479" height="107" />', '', 144, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(428, 'Delete Space Quota ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete a space quota definition and un-assign the space quota from all spaces.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-space-quota SPACE_QUOTA_NAME [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n\r\n<ol>-f stands for force deletion of the targeted space quota without confirmation or warning.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/103.png" alt="" width="726" height="159" />', '', 145, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(429, 'Set Space Quota', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to assign a space quota definition to a space.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf set-space-quota SPACE_NAME SPACE_QUOTA_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/104.png" alt="" width="844" height="83" />', '', 146, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(430, 'Unset Space Quota', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to un-assign a space quota definition from a space.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf unset-space-quota SPACE_NAME SPACE_QUOTA_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/105.png" alt="" width="897" height="112" />', '', 147, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(431, 'Service Brokers ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of service brokers.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf service-brokers</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/106.png" alt="" width="1006" height="619" />', '', 148, 1, 0, 0, 17, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(432, 'Create Service Broker', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create a new service broker.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-service-broker SERVICE_BROKER USERNAME PASSWORD URL [--space-scoped]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>\r\n--space-scoped stands for making the broker''s service plans only visible within the targeted space</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/107.png" alt="" width="1185" height="147" />', '', 149, 1, 0, 0, 17, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(433, 'Update Service Broker', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to update an existing service broker.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf update-service-broker SERVICE_BROKER USERNAME PASSWORD URL</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/108.png" alt="" width="1146" height="72" />', '', 150, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(434, 'Delete Service Broker ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete an existing service broker.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-service-broker SERVICE_BROKER [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>\r\n-f stands for force deletion of the targeted service broker without confirmation or warning.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/109.png" alt="" width="725" height="120" />', '', 151, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(435, 'Rename Service Broker', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to rename an existing service broker.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf rename-service-broker SERVICE_BROKER NEW_SERVICE_BROKER</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/110.png" alt="" width="840" height="80" />', '', 152, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(436, 'Migrate Service Instances', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to migrate service instances from one service plan to another.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf migrate-service-instances v1_SERVICE v1_PROVIDER v1_PLAN v2_SERVICE v2_PLAN</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>\r\n-f stands for force migration of the targeted service instance without confirmation or warning.</ol>\r\n', '', 153, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(437, 'Purge Service Offering', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to recursively remove a service and child objects from Cloud Foundry database without making requests to a service broker.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf purge-service-offering SERVICE [-p PROVIDER] [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>\r\n	-f stands for force deletion without confirmation\r\n	-p stands for provider\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/111.png" alt="" width="1185" height="183" />', '', 154, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(438, 'Purge Service Instance', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to recursively remove a service instance and child objects from Cloud Foundry database without making requests to a service broker.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf purge-service-instance SERVICE_INSTANCE</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>-f stands for force deletion without confirmation</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/112.png" alt="" width="1185" height="147" />', '', 155, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(439, 'Service Access', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of service access setting parameters.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf service-access [-b BROKER] [-e SERVICE] [-o ORG]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>-b stands for access for plans of a particular broker\r\n	-e stands for accessing service name of a particular service offering\r\n	-o stands for plans accessible by a particular organization</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/113.png" alt="" width="644" height="342" />', '', 156, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(440, 'Enable Service Access', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to enable access to a service or service plan for one or all orgs.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf enable-service-access SERVICE [-p PLAN] [-o ORG]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>-o enables access for a specified organization\r\n-p enables access to a specified service plan\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/114.png" alt="" width="1037" height="87" />', '', 157, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(441, 'Disable Service Access', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to disable access to a service or service plan for one or all orgs.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf disable-service-access SERVICE [-p PLAN] [-o ORG]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>-o disables access for a specified organization\r\n-p disables access to a specified service plan</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/115.png" alt="" width="1058" height="91" />', '', 158, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(442, 'Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a single security group.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf security-group SECURITY_GROUP</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/116.png" alt="" width="652" height="505" />', '', 159, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(443, 'Security Groups', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of all security groups.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf security-groups</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/117.png" alt="" width="488" height="205" />', '', 160, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(444, 'Create Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to create a new security group.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf create-security-group SECURITY_GROUP_PATH_TO_JSON_RULES_FILE</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/118.png" alt="" width="1094" height="81" />', '', 161, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018');
INSERT INTO `wp_spider_faq_question` (`id`, `title`, `category`, `article`, `fullarticle`, `ordering`, `published`, `like`, `unlike`, `hits`, `user_name`, `date`) VALUES
(445, 'Update Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to update an existing security group.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf update-security-group SECURITY_GROUP_PATH_TO_JSON_RULES_FILE</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/119.png" alt="" width="1116" height="164" />', '', 162, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(446, 'Delete Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to delete an existing security group.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf delete-security-group SECURITY_GROUP [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>-f stands for force deletion of the targeted security group without confirmation or warning.</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/120.png" alt="" width="811" height="140" />', '', 163, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(447, 'Bind Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to bind a security group to a particular space, or all existing spaces of an org.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf bind-security-group SECURITY_GROUP ORG [SPACE]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/121.png" alt="" width="1007" height="84" />', '', 164, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(448, 'Unbind Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to unbind a security group from a space.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf unbind-security-group SECURITY_GROUP ORG SPACE</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/122.png" alt="" width="1041" height="177" />', '', 165, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(449, 'Bind Staging Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to bind a security group to the list of security groups to be used for staging applications.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf bind-staging-security-group SECURITY_GROUP</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/123.png" alt="" width="1019" height="93" />', '', 166, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(450, 'Staging Security Groups', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of security groups in the staging set for applications.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf staging-security-groups</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/124.png" alt="" width="753" height="241" />', '', 167, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(451, 'Unbind Staging Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to unbind a security group from the set of security groups for staging applications.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf unbind-staging-security-group SECURITY_GROUP</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/125.png" alt="" width="1094" height="182" />', '', 168, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(452, 'Bind Running Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to bind a security group to the list of security groups to be used for running applications.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf bind-running-security-group SECURITY_GROUP</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/126.png" alt="" width="1070" height="186" />', '', 169, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(453, 'Running Security Groups', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of security groups in the set of security groups for running applications.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf running-security-groups</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/127.png" alt="" width="779" height="248" />', '', 170, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(454, 'Unbind Running Security Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to unbind a security group from the set of security groups for running applications.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf unbind-running-security-group SECURITY_GROUP</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/128.png" alt="" width="1072" height="183" />', '', 171, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(455, 'Running Environment Variable Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to retrieve the contents of the running environment variable group.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf running-environment-variable-group</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/129.png" alt="" width="909" height="131" />', '', 172, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(456, 'Staging Environment Variable Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to retrieve the contents of the staging environment variable group.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf staging-environment-variable-group</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/130.png" alt="" width="930" height="138" />', '', 173, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(457, 'Set Staging Environment Variable Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to pass parameters as JSON to create a staging environment variable group.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf set-staging-environment-variable-group ''{"name":"value","name":"value"}''</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/131.png" alt="" width="1239" height="90" />', '', 174, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(458, 'Set Running Environment Variable Group', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to pass parameters as JSON to create a running environment variable group.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf set-running-environment-variable-group ''{"name":"value","name":"value"}'' </p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/132.png" alt="" width="1241" height="88" />', '', 175, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(459, 'Feature Flags', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to retrieve list of feature flags with status of each flag-able feature.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf feature-flags</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/133.png" alt="" width="685" height="423" />', '', 176, 1, 0, 0, 18, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(460, 'Feature Flag', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to retrieve an individual feature flag with status.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf feature-flag FEATURE_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/134.png" alt="" width="939" height="158" />', '', 177, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(461, 'Enable Feature Flag', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to enable the use of a feature so that users have access to and can use the feature.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf enable-feature-flag FEATURE_NAME </p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/135.png" alt="" width="1029" height="160" />', '', 178, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(462, 'Disable Feature Flag', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to disable the use of a feature so that users have access to and can use the feature.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf disable-feature-flag FEATURE_NAME </p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/136.png" alt="" width="1102" height="168" />', '', 179, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(463, 'CURL', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to execute a raw request to the targeted API endpoint.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf curl PATH [-iv] [-X METHOD] [-H HEADER] [-d DATA] [--output FILE]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nWhere:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style="list-style-type: none">\r\n<ol>-H stands for custom headers to include in the request, flag can be specified multiple times</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style="list-style-type: none">\r\n<ol>-X stands for HTTP method (GET,POST,PUT,DELETE,etc)</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style="list-style-type: none">\r\n<ol>-d stands for HTTP data to include in the request body, or ''@'' followed by a file name to read the data from</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li style="list-style-type: none">\r\n<ol>-i stands for include response headers in the output</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ol>--output stands for write curl body to FILE instead of stdout</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '', 180, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(464, 'Config ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to write default values to the configuration.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf config [--async-timeout TIMEOUT_IN_MINUTES] [--trace (true | false | path/to/file)] [--color (true | false)] [--locale (LOCALE | CLEAR)]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>\r\n--async-timeout stands for timeout for async HTTP requests\r\n	--color stands for enabling or disabling color\r\n	--locale stands to set default locale. If LOCALE is ''CLEAR'', previous locale is deleted.\r\n	--trace traces HTTP requests</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/138.png" alt="" width="892" height="53" />', '', 181, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(465, 'Oauth Token', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to retrieve and display the OAuth token for the current session.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf oauth-token</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/139.png" alt="" width="1248" height="151" />', '', 182, 1, 0, 0, 16, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(466, 'SSH Code', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to receive a one-time password for SSH clients.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf ssh-code</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/140.png" alt="" width="581" height="77" />', '', 183, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(467, 'Add Plugin Repo', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to add a new plugin repository.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf add-plugin-repo REPO_NAME URL</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/141.png" alt="" width="1221" height="72" />', '', 184, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(468, 'Remove Plugin Repo', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to remove a plugin repository.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf remove-plugin-repo REPO_NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/142.png" alt="" width="823" height="129" />', '', 185, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(469, 'List Plugin Repos', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of all the added plugin repositories.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf list-plugin-repos</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/143.png" alt="" width="740" height="170" />', '', 186, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(470, 'Repo Plugins', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of all the available plugins in all added repositories.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf repo-plugins [-r REPO_NAME]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>-r stands for name of a registered repository</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/144.png" alt="" width="1248" height="587" />\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/145.png" alt="" width="1247" height="422" />', '', 187, 1, 0, 0, 14, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(471, 'Plugins ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to view a list of all the installed plugin commands.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf plugins [--checksum | --outdated]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>--checksum stands for computing and showing the sha1 value of the plugin binary file\r\n	--outdated stands for searching the plugin repositories for new versions of installed plugins\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/145.png" alt="" width="1060" height="175" />', '', 188, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(472, 'Install Plugin', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to install the plugin defined in command argument.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf install-plugin PLUGIN_NAME [-r REPO_NAME] [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf install-plugin LOCAL-PATH/TO/PLUGIN | URL [-f]</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nWhere:\r\n	<ol>-f stands for force install of plugin without confirmation\r\n	-r stands for restricting search for plugin to this registered repository</ol>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/147.png" alt="" width="1247" height="201" />', '', 189, 1, 0, 0, 18, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(473, 'Uninstall Plugin ', 4, 'Purpose:\r\n\r\nUse this command to uninstall the plugin defined in command argument.\r\n\r\nSyntax:\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">$ cf uninstall-plugin PLUGIN-NAME</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\nExample:\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-304" src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/acf-console/user-guide/148.png" alt="" width="781" height="102" />', '', 190, 1, 0, 0, 15, 'suchita', '04-04-2018'),
(474, 'How can I run my applications on Cloud Foundry?', 1, '<ul>\r\n     <li>Download and install -https://github.com/cloudfoundry/cli/releases the CLI tool suitable \r\n         for your Operating System.</li>\r\n     <li>Target and login to your CF API endpoint via the CLI.</li>\r\n     <li>Once logged in, create and target an Organization, then create a Space and target the same \r\n         using CLI.</li>\r\n     <li>Push your cloud-ready application using the CLI commands.</li>\r\n     <li>If you wish to use any of CF service, bind it with your application and restage it.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n', '', 191, 1, 0, 0, 22, 'suchita', '05-04-2018'),
(478, ' What are the services offered for a shared ACF platform user?', 1, 'After targeting and logging into Atos Cloud Foundry, run the cf marketplace cf CLI command to view the services available to your targeted organization.\r\n\r\nAvailable services may differ between organizations and between Atos Cloud Foundry marketplaces.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Usage</em>:  <b>cf marketplace</b> [-s SERVICE]\r\n\r\n<strong>Alias</strong>\r\n\r\nm\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div><strong>Options</strong></div>\r\n<div>-s</div>\r\n<dl>\r\n 	<dd>Show plan details for a particular service offering.</dd>\r\n 	<dd></dd>\r\n 	<dt><span class="option-name">--no-plans</span></dt>\r\n 	<dd>Hide plan information for service offerings</dd>\r\n</dl>', '', 192, 1, 0, 0, 5, 'admin', '21-05-2019'),
(484, 'What are the roles and their responsibilities on the ACF platform?', 1, 'The following describes each type of user role in Atos Cloud Foundry:-\r\n\r\n<strong>Org Managers</strong>: Administer the org.\r\n\r\n<strong>Org Auditors</strong>: Read-only access to user information and org quota usage information.\r\n\r\n<strong>Org Users</strong>: Read-only access to the list of other org users and their roles. When an Org Manager gives a person an Org or Space role, that person automatically receives Org User status in that org.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Space Managers:</strong> Administer a space within an org.\r\n\r\n<strong>Space Developers</strong>: Manage applications and services in a space.\r\n\r\n<strong>Space Auditors:</strong> Read-only access to a space.', '', 193, 1, 0, 0, 6, 'admin', '22-05-2019'),
(496, 'What are the tools that are used for Platform Operations control?', 1, '<strong>Pingdom</strong>: Monitor and tests the availability of our website, applications and servers.Automated the pingdom interactions with our REST API.Get to the root of any server or application outage to resolve the issue and prevent any recurrence.\r\n\r\n<strong>Nagios</strong>: Offers monitoring and alerting services for servers, switches, applications and services. It alerts when things go wrong and alerts within a second time when the problem has been resolved.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Prometheus</strong>:Provide powerful metrics collection and alerting system. Grafana is one of the best visualization tools which can be used with Prometheus. We can create a dashboard with multiple charts together in Grafana. Grafana has out-of-the-box integration with Prometheus\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Statuspage</strong>:- Its a Communication tool that helps us to inform our users about outages and scheduled maintenance.Users can subscribe to updates via email or text messages when we have an incident.\r\n\r\n"<a href="https://eu01-cf.statuspage.io/">https://eu01-cf.statuspage.io/</a>"\r\n\r\n"<strong>ELK</strong>" is the acronym for three open source projects: Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana. Elasticsearch is a search and analytics engine. Logstash is a server side data processing pipeline that ingests data from multiple sources simultaneously, transforms it, and then sends it to a "stash" like Elasticsearch. Kibana lets users visualize data with charts and graphs in Elasticsearch.', '', 194, 1, 0, 0, 5, 'admin', '22-05-2019'),
(502, ' How to get started with ELK for application logging?', 1, 'Kibana is an analytics and visualization platform that builds on Elastic-search to give you a better understanding of your data\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Kibana Visualization</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Kibana Visualize page is where you can create, modify, and view your own custom visualizations. There are several different types of visualizations, ranging from <em>Vertical bar</em> and <em>Pie</em>charts to <em>Tile maps</em> (for displaying data on a map) and <em>Data tables</em>.\r\n\r\nWe have created few visualization for you , by which you can check specific logs and narrow down the search result. In the picture depicted below you can see what all  visualization are available for you.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Kibana Dashboard</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Kibana Dashboard page is where you can create, modify, and view your own custom dashboards. With a dashboard, you can combine multiple visualizations onto a single page, then filter them by providing a search query or by selecting filters by clicking elements in the visualization. Dashboards are useful for when you want to get an overview of your logs, and make correlations among various visualizations and logs.\r\n\r\nDashboards can be filtered further by entering a search query, changing the time filter, or clicking on the elements within the visualization.\r\n\r\nFor example, if you click on a particular color segment in the histogram, Kibana will allow you to filter on the significant term that the segment represents.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Kibana Settings</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Kibana Settings page lets you change a variety of things like default values or index patterns', '', 195, 1, 0, 0, 5, 'admin', '22-05-2019');
